node.text:
This one goes in the Reverb Tip “HALL OF FAME”
⁣
⁣⁣
Watch the video to fully see how to go about “syncing” your pre-delay to the BPM of your track! ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Pre-delay is the amount of time it takes until the initial onset of reverb.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
⁣⁣
What do we use it for?⁣⁣
⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Mainly to create separation between our original sound, and the reverb itself. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
If that reverb begins immediately, it can wash away some of the punch/transients/clarity of our sound. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Because pre-delay introduces a timing difference, it can quickly muddy things up if it’s not rhythmically delaying with the rest of your mix. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
It can create an odd hiccup where things sound out of time. Similar to when you first begin DJ’ing and can’t beat match 😭⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Some reverbs have this “tempo sync” feature already built in. Theres also a formula to do this “delay calculator” trick. Honestly, it’s much quicker to just bookmark this page!⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Type your BPM, and try out different values. See which seems to “gel” the reverb to your mix best!⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Works great on vocals, leads, drums, and more. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣

We recommend this when you're STUCK! 👇 Read More👇⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
Have you ever wanted to produce in a genre that you're maybe not too familiar with? You're not sure what elements are needed...🤔⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
Or have you ever been working and thought "this feels empty and I have no more ideas of what to add..."🤔⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
Say hello to the "Three Column Technique". This little trick helps you in two ways:⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
1 - Will make sure you have all the most important elements that make up a certain section of your song, for the specific genre that you're working in. (drop, breakdown, buildup, etc).⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
2 - Provide you a ton of ideas to experiment with, in regards to filling out your mix / song.⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
📓 🖊Start with a pen and paper and create 3 columns. You'll also need THREE reference tracks in the same genre.⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
Typically you want to do this for a specific section of the track. Lets say its the drop section...you're going to write every sound you hear in all three drops (as pictured above).⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
Next, you're going to circle any elements that appear in ALL three songs. These elements are "must have", foundational elements for this section, in this genre! You have to have these in your track.⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
With the remaining elements that aren't circled, you can experiment adding them to your own track. These provide inspiration for other elements that already worked in other songs...why not try em in yours!⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
You can repeat this process for all the different sections! Intros, buildups, drops, breaks, and so on. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣

node.text:
💎 Don't LIMIT yourself by not knowing how to use/control a LIMITER!
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
Limiters are important tools, that we use in sound design, mixing, and mastering! Use this cheat sheet to help you further understand how to use a limiter. Below, are a few more notes on some of the parameters.⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
🎛Gain / Input Knob - Limiting won't begin until our signal exceeds the threshold. When we mix quiet, we need to often add input level to our signal so it can reach the THRESHOLD, and limiting / gain reduction can begin.⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
🎛Gain Reduction - With a good mix and a high quality limiter, you can typically get away with 3-5db of reduction. Always use your ears though...if you hear distortion, lower your input and do less reduction.⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
⁣
🎛Release - Generally, shorter release times are punchier and louder. Longer times will give a cleaner result.⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
🎛Lookahead - shorter lookahead times will give you more loudness, but also more distortion. When using short lookahead times, utilize higher oversampling rates.⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
🎛Attack - some limiters will give you control over the attack. Just like a compressor, these will tame transients. At the mastering stage however, problem transients should have already been addressed. Be careful, setting extremely short attack times can "dull" transients. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣

♥️ if you love saturation like we do! ⁣
⁣
⁣
We always hear people shouting “SATURATE EVERYTHING” and they’re not necessarily wrong 😂. It sounds amazing! ⁣
⁣
Let’s take a look at what is actually happening when we saturate our signal, and why it does sound so good! ⁣
⁣
For this example, I’m playing a sine wave.⁣
⁣
A sine will produce one fundamental frequency...the note you play...nothing else, no overtones.⁣
⁣
Notice when I begin to turn the softube saturation knob (free plugin) it begins to add distortion. Those peaks however are not “random” like digital distortion!⁣
⁣
The added peaks are happening on other harmonic notes/frequencies based on the root I played (C). This is harmonic distortion.⁣
⁣
Some of the peaks added: higher octave C, G which is the 5th of the C scale, E which is the third, etc! ⁣
⁣
You can utilize saturation on many sounds. Vocals, drums, instruments and more! ⁣
⁣
You can also saturate several different ways, which will provide slightly different colors and sounds! (Tape, tube, etc) ⁣
⁣
Hope this was interesting and be sure to follow @cosmicacademy for daily tips and motivation! ⁣
⁣
⁣
